rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv64-elf: validating the Plan9 riscv64 linker's ELF output (-H 5)

WHAT THIS IS
------------
Not a compiler-correctness test (see rv_baremetal-boot-plan9-riscv64-
test-*) - this validates the LINKER's ELF-emission path itself
(sys/src/cmd/il/elf.c/elf.h, selected via `-H 5`). Plan9 doesn't use
ELF natively, but a correctly-formed ELF is useful for feeding this
project's output into standard tools (gdb, objdump, readelf, IDA/
Ghidra, etc.) on another system instead of hand-decoding or using the
`-b binary --adjust-vma` workaround this project has relied on so far.

main.c/start.s are deliberately trivial (UART hello + halt) - every
C-language and calling-convention question is already answered by
earlier folders; this one is purely about the container format.

WHAT WAS WRONG WITH THE OLDER `main.elf` TARGETS
---------------------------------------------------
Every earlier project's mkfile had a `main.elf` target commented
`# ELF is questionable`, always built with just `-H 5` and no other
flags. Reading elf.c directly explains why:

  - Section headers (.text/.data/.strtab) are only emitted if
    `debug['S']` is set (`elf32sectab`/`elf64sectab`, both gated on
    `if(debug['S'])`) - i.e. only if `-S` is passed. Without it,
    `e_shoff` and `e_shnum` are both written as 0: a technically valid
    ELF, but with no section table for a tool to anchor .text/.data to.
    That alone would make most tools show little to nothing useful.
  - The Plan9-format symbol table (from asmsym(), same one `-s` strips
    from a raw `-H 1` binary) is described by a `NOPTYPE` (type 0,
    effectively unused) program header when present, not an ELF
    `SHT_SYMTAB` section - external tools cannot read it as symbols
    either way, so leaving it in only adds inert bytes. Stripped here
    with `-s`, same as every other main.bin target in this project.

This folder's main.elf target uses `-s -S -H 5` instead of just `-H 5`.

WHAT WAS CHECKED BEFORE BUILDING
------------------------------------
elf.h's machine-type enum has `RISCV = 243`, matching the real ELF
spec's EM_RISCV value - so obj.c's `elf64(243, ELFDATA2LSB, 0, nil)`
call (see il/asm.c's HEADTYPE switch) targets the right architecture
code. class/data/version/entry point/program header fields in
elf32()/elf64() all looked like a standard, unremarkable ELF writer on
read-through - nothing else stood out as suspicious before building
this.

THREE MORE REAL BUGS FOUND BUILDING/VALIDATING THIS FOLDER
----------------------------------------------------------------
Confirming "-s -S -H 5" actually produces a clean, tool-readable ELF
took three more fix/rebuild/re-validate rounds, each caught by running
real tooling against the output rather than trusting source review
alone:

  1. `.strtab`'s declared section size was hardcoded to 14 bytes in
     both elf32sectab()/elf64sectab(), but elfstrtab() actually writes
     22 bytes (".text\0.data\0.strtab\0" plus a leading and trailing
     NUL). readelf -S showed the truncation directly: the .strtab
     section's own name (which lives inside the truncated region)
     came back as "." instead of ".strtab". Fixed: both hardcoded `14`
     literals changed to `22`.

  2. `objdump -h`/`-d` still showed nothing for .text even after fix
     #1, despite readelf reading it fine. Cause: the ELF spec requires
     section-header-table index 0 to be a reserved, all-zero SHT_NULL
     entry; elf32sectab()/elf64sectab() never wrote one, emitting
     .text directly as entry 0 instead. readelf is lenient and takes
     the file at face value; objdump's BFD library assumes spec
     compliance, silently treats entry 0 as the implicit reserved
     section, and discards it - which looked exactly like .text
     vanishing from its section listing. Fixed: added a genuine
     10-zero-argument elf64shdr()/elf32shdr() call before the .text
     one in both functions, bumped the Shdr count (3->4) and .strtab's
     index (2->3) in elf32()/elf64()'s debug['S'] block, and bumped
     the "3*ShdrXXsz" offset math for .strtab's file position to
     "4*ShdrXXsz" to account for the extra header.

  3. Even after fix #2, objdump -d disassembled garbage for the first
     72 bytes of .text before real code appeared around offset 0x60.
     Comparing main.elf's raw .text bytes against the known-good
     main.bin byte-for-byte showed the corruption started at byte 0
     and ended exactly at byte 0x48 (72 decimal) - not a coincidence.
     Cause: obj.c's HEADR calculation for HEADTYPE 5 (elf executable)
     was hardcoded to 32-bit sizes - `rnd(52+3*32, 16) = 160` (using
     Ehdr32sz=52, Phdr32sz=32) - regardless of thechar. asmb() writes
     the actual code starting at file offset HEADR (160) BEFORE
     elf64() runs; elf64() later seeks to file offset 0 and writes a
     real 64-bit Ehdr+3 Phdrs (64+3*56=232 bytes, ending at file offset
     232) - which overlaps and overwrites the first 232-160=72 bytes of
     the code already written at 160. Fixed: obj.c's HEADR line now
     reads `thechar == 'j' ? rnd(64L+3*56L, 16) : rnd(52L+3*32L, 16)` -
     240 for riscv64 (leaving no overlap), unchanged 160 for riscv32.

All three are now hardware/tool confirmed fixed: objdump -d produces
clean, correct disassembly starting exactly with the expected setSB/
stack-setup/jump-to-main sequence (auipc gp,... / addi gp,gp,... /
auipc sp,... / addi sp,sp,... / auipc a0,... / addi a0,a0,... / jr a0),
matching every hand-decode done elsewhere in this project byte for
byte, with standard ABI register names resolved automatically by the
tooling instead of Plan9's raw register numbers.

HOW TO VALIDATE (on this Linux host, once main.elf is built)
-----------------------------------------------------------------
    file main.elf
        # expect: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, UCB RISC-V, ...

    readelf -h main.elf
        # e_type=EXEC, e_machine=RISC-V, e_entry should be a real
        # 0x410000xx address (not 0), e_shoff/e_shnum should be
        # non-zero this time (that's the -S fix)

    readelf -l main.elf
        # expect 3 PT_LOAD/NOPTYPE program headers (text, data, and a
        # now-empty symbol-table placeholder since -s zeroed symsize)
        # with sane vaddr/filesz/memsz around 0x41000000

    readelf -S main.elf
        # expect .text, .data, .strtab with the right sizes/addresses

    riscv64-linux-gnu-objdump -d main.elf
        # this is the actual payoff: unlike every earlier folder in
        # this project, this should disassemble WITHOUT needing
        # `-b binary -m riscv:rv64 --adjust-vma=<addr>` - objdump reads
        # the entry point, section boundaries, and architecture
        # straight from the ELF headers if they're correct.

STRONGER VALIDATION (optional, on real hardware) - TRIED, INCONCLUSIVE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
U-Boot has a `bootelf` command that parses and loads an ELF image
according to its own program/section headers, unlike `go` which just
jumps to a raw address - a real independent ELF loader validating the
file, not just static analysis tools. Tried on this board (U-Boot
2022.10, Allwinner): `fatload mmc 0:1 ${loadaddr} main.elf` loaded the
file correctly (confirmed byte-for-byte against the host-built file via
`md ${loadaddr} 10` - every ELF header field matched: e_machine=243,
e_entry=0x41000000, e_shnum=4, e_shstrndx=3, etc.), but `bootelf -p`/
`-s`/default all returned to the prompt instantly with zero output -
no error, no hang, no UART line - and `bootelf -p ${loadaddr}; echo
rc=$?` reported rc=0 ("success") despite no observable effect.

Given main.c's main() never returns (infinite loop) once reached, the
instant, clean return to the U-Boot prompt most likely means execution
never reached it - plausibly a fault (e.g. from bootelf calling the
entry point as a C function call rather than a bare jump, which our
_start/main was never designed to tolerate - it only ever expected
`go`'s "jump and never return" contract) getting silently caught by
U-Boot's own S-mode trap handler and resuming the shell, similar in
spirit to how rv_baremetal-boot-linux-wdt-clk-mode's start.S
deliberately catches CSR-probe faults the same way - just happening
here as an unplanned side effect. Confirming this precisely would need
this board's exact U-Boot source for cmd/elf.c, which wasn't available
to check.

Conclusion: this is inconclusive about *this board's U-Boot bootelf
implementation*, not a reflection on the ELF file's correctness - the
file is already independently confirmed correct three separate ways
(file/readelf/objdump on the host, plus byte-exact in live board RAM).
Not pursued further; the static-tooling validation above is considered
sufficient and this folder's goal (a correct, standards-compliant,
externally-tool-readable ELF) is met.

BUILD
-----
mk (produces main.bin, the known-good raw flashable image, and
main.elf, the ELF image under test). objtype=riscv64 is set at the top
of the mkfile.
